axis2.name: Delay Ratio
axis2.text:
SUM(CASE WHEN 
    CASE WHEN ISNULL(<%=due_date%>)=1 THEN NULL 
    
         WHEN ISNULL(PU_LAST(VBAP,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.EVENTTIME,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.ACTIVITY_EN = <%=real_date%>))=1 AND
              HOURS_BETWEEN(<%=due_date%>,TO_TIMESTAMP('<%=today_help%>','YYYY-MM-DD')) >= (24.0 + 24.0* <%=buffer%>) THEN 1
              
         WHEN ISNULL(PU_LAST(VBAP,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.EVENTTIME,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.ACTIVITY_EN = <%=real_date%>))=1 THEN 2
         
         WHEN HOURS_BETWEEN(<%=due_date%>,PU_LAST(VBAP,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.EVENTTIME,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.ACTIVITY_EN = <%=real_date%>)) >= (24.0 + 24.0* <%=buffer%>) THEN 1
         
         WHEN HOURS_BETWEEN(<%=due_date%>,PU_LAST(VBAP,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.EVENTTIME,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.ACTIVITY_EN = <%=real_date%>)) < (24.0 + 24.0* <%=buffer%>) THEN 0
         
         ELSE 3 END in(1)
         
         THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)*1.0

/

SUM(CASE WHEN 
    CASE WHEN ISNULL(<%=due_date%>)=1 THEN NULL 
    
         WHEN ISNULL(PU_LAST(VBAP,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.EVENTTIME,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.ACTIVITY_EN = <%=real_date%>))=1 AND
              HOURS_BETWEEN(<%=due_date%>,TO_TIMESTAMP('<%=today_help%>','YYYY-MM-DD')) >= (24.0 + 24.0* <%=buffer%>) THEN 1
              
         WHEN ISNULL(PU_LAST(VBAP,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.EVENTTIME,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.ACTIVITY_EN = <%=real_date%>))=1 THEN 2
         
         WHEN HOURS_BETWEEN(<%=due_date%>,PU_LAST(VBAP,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.EVENTTIME,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.ACTIVITY_EN = <%=real_date%>)) >= (24.0 + 24.0* <%=buffer%>) THEN 1
         
         WHEN HOURS_BETWEEN(<%=due_date%>,PU_LAST(VBAP,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.EVENTTIME,_CEL_O2C_ACTIVITIES.ACTIVITY_EN = <%=real_date%>)) < (24.0 + 24.0* <%=buffer%>) THEN 0
         
         ELSE 3 END in(0,1)
         
         THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)*1.0

components.title: Model Input Features

components.message: With the help of the results of the feature selection algorithm, you can now select the features/columns that you want to use for the model by adding them to the 'model_input_cases_table' table below. Apply your process knowledge to add further features, as the feature selection algorithm might not be able to detect all important features. In the end, the model will learn from the feature below as well as the process flow, which will be encoded and used in the background, giving the model the exact information for each input. You can also add custom KPIs on the next sheet. After selecting the input features, go to the ML Workbench and run the Notebook.

formula.name: Single KPI
formula.text: COUNT(DISTINCT CASE WHEN "Py_DDP_Feature_recommendation"."table" || '.' || "Py_DDP_Feature_recommendation"."column" in (<%=case_features%>) THEN "Py_DDP_Feature_recommendation"."table" || '.' || "Py_DDP_Feature_recommendation"."column"  ELSE NULL END)

components.message: The feature selection algorithm searches all tables of the datamodel and calculates the correlation for continuous columns and Cramer's V for categorical columns. These two metrics show how equally the delay rate is distributed among the different values in the column. If it is perfectly equally distributed, the column has no impact on the delay rate and is of no interest for the model (metric close to 0). If however, the distribution is very imbalanced, the column helps in seperationg delayed items from on time items (metric close to 1).  Take a closer look at the features in the next step.

Below you can take a look at the suggested features from step 1. To inspect a feature select it in the dropdown. If a feature has high difference in delay rate among different categories that also cover a good share of the cases it should be included in the model. You can add a feature as model input with the dropdown in step 3. There you can also see all the selected features. Make sure not to select highly correlated features like MATNR and MATNR_TEXT.
